Title: A thanks to the traits working group in 2021
Description: So…this is awkward. I wanted to write this post near the end of 2021 or beginning of 2022, but time got away from me, as it does so often. However, a half-completed draft has been open in my browser this entire time, and I think it’d be a shame for it to go to waste and not celebrate all the work done on traits working-group related things and to celebrate the people who have done that amazing work. Given that this is “unofficial” though, I’ll be a little less formal than I otherwise would if this was posted to the Inside Rust Blog.

Title: ImageSharp 2.0.0: The Feature-Packed Release
Description: ImageSharp, one of the most popular .NET image-processing libraries, released version 2 of their library. The release includes major features such as supporting WebP, TIFF and PBM as well adding XMP support with various performance improvements and enhancements for JPEG and PNG formats. This release drops support for .NET Standard 1.3. The update replaces version 1.0.4.

Title: A way out for a.out
Description:
The a.out executable
format dates back to the earliest days of Linux — and before.  It has
not been used in any serious way for decades, but support still exists in
the Linux kernel and has resisted all attempts at its removal.  Back in
January, Borislav Petkov tried yet
again to delete support for this format, leading to another extended
discussion.  There is one difference this time around, though: the effort
to get rid of a.out support might just succeed.
